        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer14212588" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8617497860928532197">I sat down and read this book in an evening because I love food and I love the idea that people go do these crazy, rigorous courses in other countries to learn how to cook incredible food, every time. And they talk about tasty, tasty food a lot. There is a recipe at the end of every chapter and most have some relation to what Kathleen is cooking as part of Le Cordon Bleu&apos;s course so most of it is very classic and meaty, which sounds great but isn&apos;t really what I cook. Don&apos;t read the book for the</span>
  <span id="freeText8617497860928532197" style="display:none">I sat down and read this book in an evening because I love food and I love the idea that people go do these crazy, rigorous courses in other countries to learn how to cook incredible food, every time. And they talk about tasty, tasty food a lot. There is a recipe at the end of every chapter and most have some relation to what Kathleen is cooking as part of Le Cordon Bleu's course so most of it is very classic and meaty, which sounds great but isn't really what I cook. Don't read the book for the recipes, read it to find out what taking a course at Le Cordon Bleu is like, and of course, to wish that your life sounded as together as Kathleen Flinn's when you put it on paper.</span>
